import requests 
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import numpy as np
import re
import pandas as pd
In[31]:
url = "https://www.flipkart.com/search?q=laptops&otracker=search&otracker1=search&marketplace=FLIPKART&as-show=on&as=off&page=1"
page = requests.get(url)
soup=BeautifulSoup(page.text)

p = soup.find_all('div',class_="Nx9bqj _4b5DiR")

prices = []
for i in p:
    prices.append(i.text)
    
data = soup.find_all("div",class_="KzDlHZ")

Brands = []
for i in data :
    Brands.append(i.text.split()[0])
    
models = []
for i in data:
    name = i.text.strip()                         
    words = re.findall(r"[A-Za-z0-9\-]+", name)   
    models.append(" ".join(words[:3]))  


RAM = []   # to store RAM values

for i in data :
    title = i.text.strip()
    
    gb_matches = re.findall(r'\d+\s*GB', title)
    
    if gb_matches:             
        RAM.append(gb_matches[0])
    else:
        RAM.append(None)

ROM = []   

for i in data :
    title = i.text.strip()

    
    rom = re.findall(r'\d+\s*GB\s*SSD|\d+\s*TB\s*SSD', title, flags=re.IGNORECASE)

    if rom:          
        ROM.append(rom[0])   
    else:
        ROM.append(None)  
        
features =soup.find_all("li",class_="J+igdf")

display = []
for i in features:
    text = i.text.strip()
    
    
    match = re.findall(r'\(([\d\.]+\s*inch)\)', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
    if match:
        display.append(match[0])  

products = soup.find_all("div", class_="tUxRFH")

ratings = []
for product in products:
    rating = product.find("div", class_="XQDdHH")
    if rating:
        ratings.append(rating.text.strip())
    else:
        ratings.append("NaN") 

data1 = soup.find_all("li",class_="J+igdf")      
processor = []

for li in data1:  # your <li> tags list
    text = li.text.strip()

   
    match = re.findall(r'((?:\w+\s*){1,4})Processor', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)

    if match:
        
        processor.append(match[-1].strip())

     "RAM":RAM,
     "ROM":ROM,
     "Display":display,
     "Price": prices,
    "Rating" : ratings,
     "Processor" : processor
    }

In[32]:
prices = []
Brands = []
models = []
RAM = []  
ROM = []  
display = []
ratings = []
processor = []

for i in range(1,50):
    print("https://www.flipkart.com/search?q=laptops&otracker=search&otracker1=search&marketplace=FLIPKART&as-show=on&as=off&page="+str(i))
    urls = "https://www.flipkart.com/search?q=laptops&otracker=search&otracker1=search&marketplace=FLIPKART&as-show=on&as=off&page=1"
    page = requests.get(urls)
    soup=BeautifulSoup(page.text)
    
    p = soup.find_all('div',class_="Nx9bqj _4b5DiR")
    
    
    for i in p:
        prices.append(i.text)
        
    data = soup.find_all("div",class_="KzDlHZ")
    
    for i in data :
        Brands.append(i.text.split()[0])
        
    for i in data:
        name = i.text.strip()                         
        words = re.findall(r"[A-Za-z0-9\-]+", name)   
        models.append(" ".join(words[:3]))  
    
    
    
    for i in data :
        title = i.text.strip()
        
        gb_matches = re.findall(r'\d+\s*GB', title)
        
        if gb_matches:             
            RAM.append(gb_matches[0])
        else:
            RAM.append(None)
    
    
    for i in data :
        title = i.text.strip()
    
        
        rom = re.findall(r'\d+\s*GB\s*SSD|\d+\s*TB\s*SSD', title, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
        if rom:          
            ROM.append(rom[0])   
        else:
            ROM.append(None)  
            
    features =soup.find_all("li",class_="J+igdf")
    
    for i in features:
        text = i.text.strip()
        
        
        match = re.findall(r'\(([\d\.]+\s*inch)\)', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
        
        if match:
            display.append(match[0])  
    
    products = soup.find_all("div", class_="tUxRFH")
    
    for product in products:
        rating = product.find("div", class_="XQDdHH")
        if rating:
            ratings.append(rating.text.strip())
        else:
            ratings.append("NaN") 
    
    data1 = soup.find_all("li",class_="J+igdf")      
    
    for li in data1:  # your <li> tags list
        text = li.text.strip()
    
       
        match = re.findall(r'((?:\w+\s*){1,4})Processor', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
        if match:
            
            processor.append(match[-1].strip())

import pandas as pd

# Load your Excel file
df = pd.read_excel("laptop_data.xlsx")

# Reorder columns: move 'Processor' before 'Rating'
cols = list(df.columns)
cols.remove('Processor')
rating_index = cols.index('Rating')
cols.insert(rating_index, 'Processor')

df = df[cols]

# Save the updated file
df.to_excel("laptops_dataset.xlsx", index=False)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load your Excel file
df = pd.read_excel("laptop1_dataset.xlsx")

# Drop the unnecessary index column if present
if 'Unnamed: 0' in df.columns:
    df = df.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0'])

# --- BASIC SUMMARY ---
print("===== Basic Info =====")
print(df.info(), "\n")

print("===== Summary Statistics =====")
print(df.describe(include='all'), "\n")

# --- UNIVARIATE ANALYSIS ---

# Separate categorical and numerical columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
numerical_cols = df.select_dtypes(exclude=['object']).columns

# ---------------- NUMERICAL VARIABLES ----------------
for col in numerical_cols:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.hist(df[col], bins=20, edgecolor='black')
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {col}")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.show()

# ---------------- CATEGORICAL VARIABLES ----------------
for col in categorical_cols:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    df[col].value_counts().head(10).plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.title(f"Top 10 categories in {col}")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.show()

# --- EXTRA CLEAN VISUALS FOR INSIGHT ---
# Example: Top 10 Brands
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
df['Brand'].value_counts().head(10).plot(kind='bar', color='lightgreen', edgecolor='black')
plt.title("Top 10 Laptop Brands")
plt.xlabel("Brand")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

# Example: Rating Distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.hist(df['Rating'], bins=10, color='orange', edgecolor='black')
plt.title("Distribution of Laptop Ratings")
plt.xlabel("Rating")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# ------------------- LOAD DATA -------------------
# Load Excel file
df = pd.read_excel("laptop1_dataset.xlsx")

# Remove unnecessary column if it exists
if 'Unnamed: 0' in df.columns:
    df = df.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0'])

# Clean the Price column (remove , commas)
df['Price'] = df['Price'].replace('[,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# ------------------- BIVARIATE ANALYSIS -------------------

# 1 PRICE vs RATING (Numerical vs Numerical)
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
plt.scatter(df['Price'], df['Rating'], alpha=0.6, color='teal', edgecolors='black')
plt.title("Price vs Rating")
plt.xlabel("Price ()")
plt.ylabel("Rating")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

# 2 AVERAGE RATING BY BRAND (Categorical vs Numerical)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
df.groupby('Brand')['Rating'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(10).plot(
    kind='bar', color='lightgreen', edgecolor='black'
)
plt.title("Average Rating by Brand (Top 10)")
plt.xlabel("Brand")
plt.ylabel("Average Rating")
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

# 3 AVERAGE PRICE BY PROCESSOR (Categorical vs Numerical)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
df.groupby('Processor')['Price'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(10).plot(
    kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black'
)
plt.title("Average Price by Processor Type (Top 10)")
plt.xlabel("Processor Type")
plt.ylabel("Average Price ()")
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

# 4 AVERAGE PRICE BY RAM SIZE (Categorical vs Numerical)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
df.groupby('RAM')['Price'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).plot(
    kind='bar', color='orange', edgecolor='black'
)
plt.title("Average Price by RAM Size")
plt.xlabel("RAM Size")
plt.ylabel("Average Price ()")
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

# ------------------- OPTIONAL INSIGHTS -------------------
# Correlation between Price and Rating
corr = df['Price'].corr(df['Rating'])
print(f"Correlation between Price and Rating: {corr:.2f}")

# Average rating by RAM
avg_rating_by_ram = df.groupby('RAM')['Rating'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
print("\nAverage Rating by RAM:")
print(avg_rating_by_ram)

#  MULTIVARIATE ANALYSIS FOR LAPTOP DATASET

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# ------------------ 1 LOAD & CLEAN DATA ------------------

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_excel("laptop1_dataset.xlsx")

# Clean column names (fix hidden spaces, case sensitivity, etc.)
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()               # remove spaces around names
df.columns = df.columns.str.replace(' ', '')      # remove spaces inside names
df.columns = df.columns.str.lower()               # convert all names to lowercase

# Drop unnecessary column if exists
if 'unnamed:0' in df.columns:
    df = df.drop(columns=['unnamed:0'])

# Clean and convert price column
df['price'] = df['price'].replace('[,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# Set Seaborn style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# ------------------ 2 PRICE, RATING & RAM ------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(
    x='ram', 
    y='price', 
    hue=pd.cut(df['rating'], bins=[0, 3, 4, 5], labels=['Low', 'Medium', 'High']),
    data=df,
    palette='coolwarm'
)
plt.title("Price Distribution by RAM and Rating Level")
plt.xlabel("RAM Size")
plt.ylabel("Price ()")
plt.legend(title='Rating Level', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# ------------------ 3 BRAND, PROCESSOR & RATING ------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
top_brands = df['brand'].value_counts().head(6).index
sns.barplot(
    x='brand', 
    y='rating', 
    hue='processor', 
    data=df[df['brand'].isin(top_brands)], 
    palette='viridis'
)
plt.title("Average Rating by Brand and Processor Type")
plt.xlabel("Brand")
plt.ylabel("Average Rating")
plt.legend(title='Processor', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# ------------------ 4 PRICE, BRAND & RATING ------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(
    x='price', 
    y='rating', 
    hue='brand', 
    data=df, 
    alpha=0.7, 
    s=70
)
plt.title("Price vs Rating (Colored by Brand)")
plt.xlabel("Price ()")
plt.ylabel("Rating")
plt.legend(title='Brand', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# ------------------ 5 CORRELATION HEATMAP ------------------
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64'])
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(numeric_df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='YlGnBu', fmt=".2f")
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Columns")
plt.show()

# ------------------ 6 PAIRPLOT ------------------
sns.pairplot(df[['price', 'rating']], diag_kind='hist')
plt.suptitle("Pairplot: Price and Rating Relationship", y=1.02)
plt.show()
